## Context Bag

### STRONGS CORE

**G2360 θροέω (throéō)** — "to clamor; by impl. to frighten." KJV: "trouble." Derivation: from root "to wail." Only 3× NT: Matt 24:6, Mk 13:7, 2 Thess 2:2. RELATED WORDS from same root: G2351 θόρυβος (thorybos)=tumult/uproar; G2355 θρῆνος (thrēnos)=wailing/lamentation; G2358 θριαμβεύω (thriambeuō)=triumph (noisy procession). Semantic field: loud emotional outcry — the SOUND of alarm. Not quiet anxiety but public panic.

**G4422 πτοέω (ptoéō)** — "to scare." KJV: "frighten/terrify." Only 2× NT: Lk 21:9, Lk 24:37. Luke's Olivet parallel uses THIS instead of G2360 — synonymous in context. Derivation: causing to fall/fly away. Conveys being STARTLED into flight.

**G5015 ταράσσω (tarassō)** — "to stir/agitate (roil water)." Used in Jn 14:1,27; 1 Pet 3:14; also Jn 12:27, 13:21 (Jesus's own soul troubled). BROADER word than G2360 — general disturbance. In Jn 14:1+27 Jesus prohibits SAME response: "let not your heart be troubled." Same discourse context as Olivet (final week instructions).

**G4531 σαλεύω (saleuō)** — "to waver, shake, agitate." 2 Thess 2:2 "not soon SHAKEN in mind" paired with G2360 "nor troubled." Also Lk 21:26 "powers of heaven shall be SHAKEN." Physical tremor + psychological destabilization.

**G674 ἀποψύχω (apopsychō)** — "to breathe out, faint." Only 1× NT: Lk 21:26 "men's hearts FAILING them for fear." Luke EXPANDS what Matt/Mk compress into G2360 — the full physiological response.

**G5401 φόβος (phobos)** — "alarm, fright." Lk 21:26 "hearts failing for FEAR." The object that causes G674 fainting.

**G181 ἀκαταστασία (akatastasia)** — "instability, disorder." Lk 21:9 "wars and COMMOTIONS." Luke substitutes this for Matt/Mk's "rumors of wars" — the same instability, different angle.

